      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The nonviolent approach, led by Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., was a crucial component of the Civil Rights Movement, but it was not the only factor that led to significant change. The nonviolent approach, while morally and strategically sound, was often hindered by its own limitations. The radical groups, such as the Black Panther Party and SNCC, brought attention to the brutal realities of racism and forced the movement to confront its own limitations. Their militant tactics, although often criticized, were a necessary response to the violence and inaction of the system. In the end, it was the combination of nonviolent pressure and radical activism that ultimately led to the passage of landmark legislation.",
